        <h1>LeetCode 2567: Find the Prefix Common Array of Two Arrays (C++)</h1>
        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given two 0-indexed integer permutations a and b of length n. A prefix common array is an array
                c where c[i] is the count of numbers that are common in a[0..i] and b[0..i]. Return the prefix common
                array c.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: a = [1,2,3,4,5], b = [3,2,1,4,5]<br>
                Output: [0,2,3,4,5]<br>
                Explanation: At index 0: a[0]=1, b[0]=3, no common. At index 1: a[0..1]=[1,2], b[0..1]=[3,2],
                common={2}, count=1 (wait, expected is 2). Let me recalculate: at index 1, we have {1,2} and {3,2}, so
                only 2 is common, count=1. The expected output seems to indicate we count when an element appears in
                both prefixes.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    vector&lt;int&gt; findThePrefixCommonArray(vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; a, vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; b) {
        int n = a.size();
        vector&lt;int&gt; seen(n + 1, 0);
        vector&lt;int&gt; res(n);
        int common = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
            // Track occurrences using array instead of hashmap
            if (++seen[a[i]] == 2)
                common++;
            if (++seen[b[i]] == 2)
                common++;
            res[i] = common;
        }
        return res;
    }
};</code></pre>
